				<div class="postbody">
				I saw on BBC that Yukos (iokoc - I think they are the same) was raided yesterday. Regardless of wether the executives are guilty of 'economic crimes' or Putin is punishing them for not towing the government line, since they are the largest oil company in Russia it will undoubtedly have an effect on the economy. Therefore, Russia is a bad bet for a little while. However, keep an eye on the economic reforms. If they are still working there may be a good time to buy soon. The temporary instability will present some opportunities to buy cheap. As long as the reforms are working and can compensate in the long run, you're good to go.
<br />

<br />
The vast majority of my stocks are in Canadian communications,  energy, banks, and bonds (I'm getting old <img src="images/smiles/wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" /> ) A much smaller amount is in American and EU (Britain, Belgium, France) investement companies. Nothing in Russia. I don't trust the stability in Russia, or Asia for that matter. The high Canadian content is also necessary so that I can get the tax deduction.
<br />

<br />
There are lots of opportunities in Eurasia and Asia. However, you need some ability and knowledge to manage investments in those environments. Personally, I don't have that ability. I want to stick my money in and not worry about it until Sept. 1, 2021.<br />
