				<div class="postbody">
				The way that the large companies were "privatized" involved using the large state owned industries as "collateral" on loans made by cronies of the folks in charge and then deliberately defaulting on the loans. The only folks who had the money to make the loans were organized crime syndicates (which really ran the soviet onion, even though they pretended to be a "socialist" country). It was their version of "starving the beast." Their idea of "capitalist reforms" are not the same as yours, even though they pretend to use the same word. 
<br />

<br />
Should you invest in russia? It really is the wild west over there. Take a look into the kidnapping/assasination rate of western businessmen. The rate of corruption in russia is about the same as in the US back in the 19th century. What they need is a Teddy Roosevelt (to clean up the cops) and an Eliot Ness (to clean up the crooks) to clean the place up. If you can weather a decade or three of economic uncertainty and banditry, you could stand to make a fortune. If next quarter is more important than the next decade, then you will lose your shirt. Anyone going there on business should expect to get fleeced (think: three card monty, spanish prisoner, 419 types) at least twice. If you expect things to be like they are here in the states, you should save time; put all your money in a pile and set fire to it. 
<br />

