			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Pick up The Economist if you want to find out more.  They have good coverage of world events, especially when there is something politically amiss.  If you want a pretty good and unslanted Russian news site, try <a href="http://www.gazeta.ru/" target="_blank">http://www.gazeta.ru/</a>  They have an English version of most articles (the Russian version is much, much better).  Avoid the Pravda site (pravda = truth in Russian) and most well-known sites based on established Russian newspapers, as they are most often politically biased.
<br />

<br />
Aside from needing better branding (Russian energy companies have boring names that almost always include what they do: Luk<span style="font-weight: bold">oil</span>, <span style="font-weight: bold">Gaz</span>prom, Sib<span style="font-weight: bold">neft</span> [neft = oil in Russian]), any large Russian corporation that turns a profit got there by using political exploits and connections after the Soviet Union collapsed in the early 90s.  It happens in America as well, but it's very cutthroat in Russia.  Energy companies, media companies, and telecom companies are all rife with corruption at this point.  Putin has some tough choices to make, because it looks like he's suppressing free trade and freedom of the press, but in actuality he may be cleansing the economy of leftover filth from the Communist days.  Russia is an emerging market currently and will be for the next decade probably and if you don't like high-risk investments, I wouldn't recommend putting your money there.
<br />

<br />
Overall, Russia isn't a big player in the oil business.  They are, however, big players in the natural gas business.  If you want to invest in oil, don't go to Russia companies for it.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
