<br />
You've obviously never been to Russia.  If you visit there for a week, you'll have a better understanding of things.  Just because the justice system and the economic system in America eventually work here in America, doesn't mean the same processes and tenets will work anywhere else.
<br />

<br />
Russia is basically the same as it was when it was the leader of the Soviet Union.  Nothing has changed.  Communists aren't seen as bad by most of the world.  Nazis, on the other hand, were.  When Germany was defeated in 1945 and when their government was reformed, <span style="font-weight: bold">everything</span> was done to expose and root out all Nazis in order to disallow them taking a role in the new government.  The thing is, if you were a male of working age, you were a member of the Nazi party during WWII.  So almost everyone was disqualified except dissenters.  
<br />

<br />
No such massive cleansing took place in Russia after the conversion.  It was okay for former Communist party members to hold office, to "run" businesses and to remain in whatever seat of power they had.  The Politburo was replaced with the Duma, but the members were the same, or at least had the same mentality.  The country has stagnated for over a decade because it's been running on Communism "light."  When the old politicians all die in about 20-30 years, you'll see significant changes.
<br />

<br />
Putin is probably doing the right thing at this point.  If the economy and government is complacent with its air of corruption, then someone has to shake things up and let them know it's not acceptable.  On the surface it may look unjust, but Russia has never been a superficial country.<br />
